Here is a sample C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    string wordToFind = "example"; // replace with the word you want to find
    int count = 0;
    ifstream file("file.txt"); // replace with the name of your text file

    // read each line of the file
    string line;
    while (file >> line) {
        // count the number of occurrences of the word in the line
        count += line.find(wordToFind) != string::npos;
    }

    cout << "The word 'example' appears " << count << " times in the file." << endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This program uses the `ifstream` class to read the text file line by line. It then uses the `string` class to search for the specified word in each line. If the word is found, the `count` variable is incremented. Finally, the program prints out the total number of occurrences of the word in the file.

Note that the `find` method of the `string` class returns the index of the first occurrence of the specified word in the string, or `string::npos` (a special value representing "not found") if the word is not found. We use this value to increment the `count` variable.

